When this rule is mentioned use this documentation:

# Dynamic Metadata

Attaching "metadata providers" to input/output Operations types, enable the platform to discover the type in runtime for fields that are partial or totally unknown in compile time.

As an example:

We have a connector with this operation which creates a "record" in a SaaS:

```dataweave
type InputParameters = {
    recordType: String,
    record: Object
}
var createRecord : Operation<InputParameters, Object, {error: String}, HttpConnection> = {
    // ...
}
```

This function is re-usable to create all kinds of entities,
but when the user wants to know the input to be completed it will be an Object with an unknown shape.

Some SaaS provide the description of an entity,
retrieving the schema describing the fields based on the customer Connection.
How can we provide this information to user? 

We need to create a metadata provider:
```dataweave
// based on a recordType name and the connection will obtain the record schema
var recordSchemaProvider: MetadataProviderExecutor<{recordType: String}, {error: String}, HttpConnection> = ... 
```
This metadata provider will retrieve a TypeValueDefinition that represents the Schema of the record type name provided as parameter. 
In case the provider fails will return an error with {error: String} shape. 


```dataweave
// example schema for recordType = "Account"
{
    name: "Account",
    "type": "Object",
    fields: [
        {
            name: {
                localName: "accountId",
                namespace: null
            },
            attributes: [],
            required: true,
            repeated: false,
            value: {
                "type" : "Number"
            },
            label: "ID",
            description: "Account Identifier"
        }
    ]
}
```

Currently, TypeValueDefinition allows describing Object, Array, Union, String, Number, Boolean and Null types.

Date and DateTime are described extending String with a format
```dataweave 
type StringFormat = "date" | "date-time"

type StringTypeValueDefinition = {|
  "type": "String",
  format?: StringFormat,
  values?: Array<EnumValue<String>>
|}
```
Number Types are described extending Number with a format
```dataweave
type NumberFormat = "integer" | "float" | "double" | "int32" | "int64"

type NumberTypeValueDefinition = {|
  "type": "Number",
  values?: Array<EnumValue<Number>>,
  format?: NumberFormat
|}
```
Additionally, enums are described setting field values for NumberTypeValueDefinition and StringTypeValueDefinition.
```dataweave
type EnumValue<T> = { value: T, label: String } 
```
     
We now need to include the newly created metadata provider in the connector declaration, like this:
```dataweave
@FlowConnectorElement()
var connector = {
    name: "WorldInfo",
    // ...
    operations: {
        ...
    },
    metadataProviders: {
        recordSchemaProvider: recordSchemaProvider,
    }
}
```

Now, we have a metadata provider which can be referenced from different operations.

We need to re-write our original operation to use the declared metadata provider:
```dataweave
type InputParameters = {
    recordType: String,
    record: @MetadataProvider(value = { name: "recordSchemaProvider", arguments: { recordType: "recordType" } }) Object
}
var createRecord : Operation<InputParameters,
                            @MetadataProvider(value = { name: "recordSchemaProvider", arguments: { recordType: "recordType" } }) Object,
                            {error: String},
                            HttpConnection> = {
    // ...
}
```

More details about referencing a metadata provider can be found in the [providers documentation](providers.md).
